Reporters visit the online mediation room at the Beijing Internet Court in Beijing, capital of China, Sept. 9, 2018. China's second internet court opened in Beijing on Sunday as authorities step up measures to protect business transactions, personal information, and intellectual property online. The Beijing Internet Court is given the jurisdiction to handle certain types of internet-related cases that should be tried by a primary-level people's court in Beijing in the first instance. Disputes in online shopping, service contracts, lending, copyrights, domains are among the typical cases. (Xinhua/Ju Huanzong)An online vendor is reportedly being sued in a public interest litigation case in East China, having been accused of selling posters which insulted Chinese heroes.In September, the procuratorate of Xihu district, Hangzhou, capital of East China's Zhejiang Province, received a complaint that a vendor surnamed Qu was selling posters that slandered Dong Cunrui and Huang Jiguang, thepaper.cn reported.Dong and Huang were two Chinese heroes who died respectively in the Liberation War and the Korea War.After an investigation, the procuratorate found that the posters included slanderous text and portraits of the heroes, and that the vendor had a "huge" supply, according to the article.The procuratorate said that the insulting words damaged the reputation of heroes and martyrs, while the online dissemination of the posters would not only defame such people, but also harm the public's social and historical sentiment as well as public interests, thepaper.cn continued.It said that Dong's close relatives were in support of the procuratorate launching public interest litigation to protect the reputation of heroes and martyrs. Huang has no remaining close relatives.On Monday, the procuratorate filed a public interest lawsuit in accordance with the Heroes and Martyrs Protection Law.The case is currently being trialed in Hangzhou Internet Court.The Heroes and Martyrs Protection Law took effect in May 2018, aiming to punish those who insult or slander heroes and martyrs and to promote the spirit of patriotism.According to the law, the names, images, reputation, and honor of heroes and martyrs are protected legally and must not be insulted, defamed, or violated by any individual. 
